    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The burning feeling you experience during a HIIT workout is often referred to as \"lactic acid soreness\" or \"metabolic fatigue.\" While the liver and shuttle are working to remove excess lactic acid, the muscle cells themselves are also responding to the buildup of lactic acid.\n\nOne key player in this process is a protein called creatine kinase (CK). CK is an enzyme that's present in the muscle cells, and it's responsible for breaking down the lactic acid that's accumulated during intense exercise. However, when the lactic acid buildup becomes too great, the CK enzyme can become saturated, leading to a buildup of lactic acid and a subsequent increase in the production of a molecule called adenosine triphosphate (ATP).\n\nATP is the energy currency of the muscle cells, and when it's released in large quantities, it can cause a sensation of burning or fatigue. This is because the ATP is binding to pain receptors on the surface of the muscle cells, sending a signal to the brain that the muscle is experiencing stress or damage.\n\nIn other words, the burning feeling you experience during a HIIT workout is not just due to the lactic acid itself, but also the downstream effects of the lactic acid buildup",
